This is the most anatomical accurate monster girls I've seen so far, congrats.
She is, indeed, a crab girl. 
The chela is very similar to a crab one (this carpus insertion is very indicative of it).
Her mouth is clearly a crab mouth, the 3rd maxilliped is very characteristic. The inside structures are not very visible, they most likely represent the two pairs of maxilla.
The ventral pleon is correct, and very characteristic of crabs.
Unfortunately, only the antenulle is visible, but  this already discards her as a scorpion gal.
This author makes better anatomy guides that the ones we use at the university. Gotta recommend this to my teacher.

Sometimes I come back to see if anyone still thinks scorpian.  I raise freshwater crabs and their claws can range from large and bulky to small and thin.  The best indicators that she is the crab is what I mentioned below.  Honestly, her face plate is the dead give away.  Face plates with eyestalk cleaners are unique specifically to the genus Cancer and aren’t found on other crustaceans or arthropods.  Other species with eye cleaners tend to have specially evolved arms or hair-like membranes on their appendages that can be used to catch detritus, which most crabs cannot do.  The only one that comes to mind is the pom-pom crab which has “hair” on their claws to more easily catch detritus in the water.   From your local fisherman, have a nice day.

Alright alright, this is ridiculous.  This girl is in fact a crab girl.  

1.) If she weren’t a crab, how could she use her bath water as soup stock?  

2.) In response to the gentleman below me, crabs, like all shellfish and crustaceans in fact have an abdomen.  Unlike insects, crabs have a “hidden” abdomen covered in armor.  

3.) The things on her face are not mandibles.  Scorpians have specialized mandibles that resemble ones like spiders.  What this girl has are exactly what crabs have, which are specialized eye-stock cleaners. 

 4.) The “natural codpiece” is something that insects and scorpians do not have, but is exactly what crabs have.  Male crabs have long thin ones to protect their genitals and females have curved large ones to carry fertilized eggs.

5.) Even accounting her extra arms, why two of them appear to be stumps/handless, in many species of fresh water crab, each pair of legs have a specific role.  In this case, they look like backlegs to flip the crab.
Huh, you learn something new everyday.
